devdoc.details: Shows how to work with fixed-size arrays in Solidity

getAllValues().details: Function to get all values in the array

getSum().details: Function to get the sum of all array elements

returns._0: The sum of all values in the array

getValue(uint256).details: Function to read a value from the array at a specific indexWARNING: No bounds checking - will revert if index is out of bounds

params.index: The position in the array to read (0 to 3)

returns._0: The value stored at the specified index

isValidIndex(uint256).details: Function to demonstrate array bounds checking

params.index: The position in the array to check

returns._0: true if the index is valid, false otherwise

length().details: Function to get the length of the array

returns._0: The length of the array (always 4 for this fixed-size array)

safeGetValue(uint256).details: Function to demonstrate safe array access with bounds checkingThis is the recommended way to access arrays in production code

params.index: The position in the array to access

returns._0: The value at the specified index

safeSetter(uint256,uint256).details: Function to demonstrate safe array update with bounds checking

params.index: The position in the array to update

setter(uint256,uint256).details: Function to update a value in the array at a specific indexWARNING: This function doesn't check bounds - accessing invalid indices will cause errorsIn production code, you should add require(index < arr.length, "Index out of bounds")

params.index: The position in the array to update (0 to 3)
params.value: The new value to store at the specified index

arr.details: Fixed-size array declaration with initializationIMPORTANT: Accessing indices outside 0-3 will cause a runtime error
